  <section class="hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>What this is</h1>
    <p class="thesis">The Mexico Brief is a site about Mexico. Mostly the economy, politics, and the relationship with the US. I keep finding other things to add.</p>
    <p>I pull together data from Banxico, INEGI, Hacienda, and other original sources and put it in one place. The peso, inflation, wages, trade, public finances, polling, crime, energy, and so on. Data is not the whole story. Obviously. But it is a much better place to start than a headline telling me what to think. I add the news that helps explain what may be happening. When I have my own view, I say so.</p>
    <p>Having it all together has been more useful than I expected. Wages make more sense next to inflation. Trade looks different next to the peso. Economic growth is worth looking at next to government approval. Those numbers normally live on completely different websites.</p>
    <p>On top stories you will see a <b>BE</b> button: the context behind the headline. The background, what is driving it, and what it changes. Written from the article and checked facts, never invented.</p>
    <p>Everything is dated and linked to the original source. You can check it, go deeper, and come to your own conclusion. If you disagree with mine, even better.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Why I made it</h2>
    <p>My name is <b>Alan Lacroix</b>. Born in Mexico City, raised in Miami, now building a business in Mexico. Somewhere along the way I realized I had lost touch with the country. The peso was at 17.5. Good or bad? The minimum wage had tripled. Why? The numbers were scattered across ten government sites and the headlines started with the conclusion. So I built this for myself. I found it extremely useful, shared it with family and friends, they did too. So I opened it up.</p>
    <p>I see Mexico partly through a US lens, and it shows in what I follow most: political stability, growth, the trade relationship, and where Mexico stands on AI, tech, and new companies.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Why should you trust me?</h2>
    <p class="lead-line">Don't. Kidding. Sort of.</p>
    <p>Every number is dated and linked to its source. Derived numbers say derived. My opinions are flagged as mine. I have no affiliation with any government or party, and nothing here is investment advice. My name is on the site. If I get something wrong, tell me.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>The email</h2>
    <p>Once a week I send the few things that actually moved, with the numbers and what I think. Never spam. Honestly, my dad could never remember the name of the site, so sending it to his inbox was easier. It works well for other people too.</p>
    <p><a class="abtn" href="/weekly.html">See what's in it and subscribe &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <p>Hopefully this brings a bit of transparency to the 13th largest economy in the world, the United States' biggest trading partner, and a team that always finds a way to exit in the first knockout round. Next World Cup is ours.</p>
    <p class="sign">Alan</p>
